Where did the Stone come from? Why does it draw lightning from the sky? Who carved the ancient runes upon it, and what do they mean? What other secrets does it hold? Perhaps the Stone…

- … is a shard of **[[36 - Primordial Powers#Primordial powers|primordial power]]**, once revered by the Makers;
- … marks **Tor**'s [[49 - Tor, the Rain-maker|Tor, the Rain-maker]] own grave;
- … was carved from **[[54 - The Whitefang Mountains#Chart a Course|Tor's Fist]]** and placed here by the god himself;
- … is the petrified remains of **[[39 - The Ruined Tower#Stormcatcher's tower|Stormcatcher]]**;
- … binds an **emanation** of the Things Below [[46 - The Things Below#**Wretch**|The Things Below]];
- … channels lightning to power an artifact deep beneath the village;
- … was brought here by the **[[45 - Tempest Lords#Tempest Lords|Tempest Lords]]** from far across land and sea;
- … is some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

What's down there, really? What did **[[30 - The Makers#The Makers|the Makers]]** build it for? Perhaps…

- … it connects to a complex of chambers and tunnels;
- … some evil thing slumbers in the water;
- … it hides an arcanum, like a variant of the **[[57 - Appendix C - Minor Arcana#A timeless vault|Preserving Runes]]** or the **[[57 - Appendix C - Minor Arcana#Ward of Still Waters Strain:|Ward of Still Waters]]**;
- … it's just a big vault for storing water (the Makers needed to drink, too);
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

What was this place, in the time of the Makers? Perhaps it was…

- … a border-fort of the **[[43 - Stone Lords#Stone Lords|Stone Lords]]**;
- … a trading post of the **[[24 - Green Lords#Green Lords|Green Lords]]**, from before the **[[12 - Fae#Fae|Fae]]**) rebelled, where they would truck with other Makers;
- … an outpost of the **[[45 - Tempest Lords#Tempest Lords|Tempest Lords]]**, watched over by **[[39 - The Ruined Tower#The Ruined Tower|Stormcatcher]]** and her tower before it fell into ruin;
- … a free city and market, where the various Makers came to trade and learn;
- … a place of pilgrimage for the Makers, a temple to whatever gods or powers they revered;
- … some combination of the above, perhaps changing over time; or
- … something else entirely.

The answer should reflect and be reflected in other details. If this was a Stone Lord border-fort, then chunks of the Old Wall could be found at the base of the bluff, down in the Great Wood. If this was a Tempest Lord outpost, then stones from the Old Wall would bear carvings like

The village has been here for a dozen generations at least, but the true origins of its people are shrouded in mystery and conflicting folktales.

Whence came the people of Stonetop? What led them to settle here? Perhaps they were…

- … subjects of **[[39 - The Ruined Tower#The Ruined Tower|Stormcatcher]]**, who fled here when her tower fell;
- … freed servants of the **[[43 - Stone Lords#Stone Lords|Stone Lords]]** and refugees from the **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]**;
- … migrants from east of the **[[11 - The Dread River#The Dread River|Dread River]]**, distant kin to the **[[34 - North Manmarch#North Manmarch|Manmarchers]]** and [[40 - South Manmarch|South Manmarch]])
- … migrants from across the **[[27 - Huffel Peaks#Huffel Peaks|Huffel Peaks]]**, who fled the boiling seas and found succor here;
- … a people out of time and space, emerging from the portal beneath the **[[39 - The Ruined Tower#The Ruined Tower|Ruined Tower]]**;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Aratis has a shrine in Stonetop's pavilion of the gods. Outside of Stonetop: consider whether this community hosts a shrine or temple to Aratis. Small shrines to Aratis might also be found at **waysides** along the Makers' Roads [[31 - The Makers' Roads#**The Crossroads**|The Makers' Roads]], or perhaps at spots where different groups of **[[26 - Hillfolk#Hillfolk|Hillfolk]]** gather and meet.

For any given shrine or temple:

- Where is it located?
- Who tends this place?
- How is Aratis herself represented?
- What symbols/trappings adorn it?
- Which of her **themes** (previous page) are emphasized?
- What high holidays are celebrated here, and how?
- What is this shrine or temple like? Perhaps it is… (pick 1)
  - … a hub of the community, a place of frequent rites, petitions, and celebrations;
  - … used only on high holidays, for each home keeps its own shrine above the hearth;
  - … neglected by most, tended only by a handful of true disciples;
  - … a grim place of judgement and punishment, shunned by all but her chosen;
  - … newly established, cramped and spare;
  - … some variation of the above; or
  - … something else entirely.

Why are the people of Barrier Pass so unwelcoming or even hostile to southerners? That's for you and your table to decide, but perhaps…

- … **Aratis** herself [[03 - Aratis, the Lawkeeper|Aratis, the Lawkeeper]] charged them to preserve the Rime Lords' teachings, and eschew the debased peoples of the south;
- … their ancestors fought off the **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]** and they still hold a grudge;
- … one of the thirteen surviving **[[38 - Rime Lords#Rime Lords|Rime Lords]]** is hidden in their mountain chambers;
- … a prophecy foretells doom coming from the south;
- … the fortress is tainted by **[[46 - The Things Below#**L'bin'bozia, Flesh-Candle, the Wax Skull, Roiling Tomb**|Y'aaw'kara]]**, and any who dwell here must guard against the **[[54 - The Whitefang Mountains#**Shantyara**|Howling Curse]]**;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something completely different.

That's for you to decide. Maybe…

- … it's a primordial **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Other primordial entities**|titan]]**, a remnant of the first age;
- … the **[[24 - Green Lords#Names|Green Lords]]** made it, as a weapon, or just because they could;
- … it's the first and oldest **[[18 - Forge Lords#**Draventao**|draventao]]**, a mighty Forge Lord who succumbed to the fire within;
- … it's a manifestation of the **[[46 - The Things Below#The Things Below|Things Below]]**, all gluttony and fire and nightmare; or
- … it's just a big, dumb beast.

Beyond the Dread River lie more ruins, bluffs and woods, and gently sloping plains. The **[[34 - North Manmarch#North Manmarch|Manmarchers]]** migrated from east of the Dread River sometime before the **[[55 - Appendix A - Ages of the World#Time of Cataclysm|Time of Cataclysm]]**. But if people dwell there still, they keep well away from the shore. And if any have ventured across the river and returned, they're keeping quiet about it.

Who or what lies east of the Dread River? That's for you and your group to decide, but perhaps one might find…

- … the husk of a sprawling empire, home now to only jackals and wolves;
- … nomadic raiders, bloody-handed even by the Manmarchers' standards;
- … descendants of the **[[30 - The Makers#The Makers|Makers]]**, greatly diminished, in isolated fiefs
- … a people in thrall to an undying sorcerer-king;
- … a land of horrors, thoroughly tainted by the **[[46 - The Things Below#The Things Below|Things Below]]**;
- … a barren land, dead and still, bereft of spirits and magic;
- … the **[[17 - Forest Folk#Forest Folk|Forest Folk]]**;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

The Fae are living beings made of spiritstuff. They aren't quite spirits, but interact with spirits as if they were. They're made of flesh and bone, or close enough, but it is strange, malleable, and resilient. They…

- … need not eat or drink, but can enjoy such fare;
- … need not sleep, but often choose to; … can suffocate or drown, but usually
- recover when they can breathe again; … feel no drive to reproduce, but might enjoy sex, fall in love, sire or bear children, steal them from mortals;
- … do not grow feeble with age, but can grow bored, deeply set in their ways;
- … cannot break a promise or an oath, but are keen at finding loopholes; and
- … feel the weight of debts and insults as though they were heavy chains.

Some entrances have special requirements to open them, for both Fae and mortal alike. These requirements might involve…

- … singing/reciting/inscribing the proper words;
- … doing something dangerous, without flinching (like running at the wall);
- … doing something daft (like spinning 'til you fall);
- … paying the toll (a secret, a story, a thing of beauty, a promise, etc.);
- … convincing the guardians to let you in;
- … some variation or combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

The residents of a domain might ignore the requirements of a locked entrance; the creator of a domain almost certainly can.

*I think my Green Lord's afterlife must certainly be locked. I imagine a grand archway with a pair of powerful Fae guardians watching over it, demanding a toll: none can enter without giving an oath of good behavior.*

, *magical*

A small bronze cauldron, full of glittering coins. At least, that's what it seems.

When you *fill the pot with small, natural items (leaves, stones, acorns, etc.) and hide it from light for a season*, the contents are glamoured to become a purse of gold (Value 4).

Any "coins" removed from the pot revert to their true form when…

- … an honest merchant touches them;
- … their current owner tells a lie;
- … someone sees through the glamour;
- … something dispels the glamour; or
- … the new moon comes and goes

The Willow Witches observe the old ways of hospitality. Any who approach peaceably and invoke the guest-right are welcome to eat their food and shelter under their roof (such that it is). The Witches will do no true harm unless the guest first violates the rules of hospitality by…

- … initiating violence;
- … threatening the Witches or their guests;
- … stealing; or
- … insulting the Witches' hospitality.

The Witches delight in provoking guests: speaking in riddles, asking about shameful secrets, offering disgusting victuals or shabby accommodations, showing glimpses of horrors that are gone when one looks again. The humble, patient, and wise do well. Hot-headed, prideful fools do not.

That's for you and your group to decide, but possibilities include...

- … they fled east, to escape the waking of the **[[08 - The Crombil#Hooks|Crombil]]**;
- … they went to fight the **[[15 - Fomoraij#Names|Fomoraij]]**, maybe at the behest of the Fae;
- … a servant of the **[[46 - The Things Below#The Things Below|Things Below]]** hunted them down, chased them off;
- … a curse transformed them into living trees, though not all at once;
- … a powerful Fae whisked them off into its domain;
- … they were ravaged by sickness; the survivors left in search of a miracle; or
- … their numbers were always few, and they simply died out.

"God" is not a distinct category of being. If a spirit or entity receives offerings and prayers, and responds in kind, then it's a god.

The origin of any given god is for you and your table to decide. A god might be…

- … one of the **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Other primordial entities**|great spirits]]**, there at the dawn of time, or birthed spontaneously from the fabric of existence, or made by the **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Cosmology**|First Creators]]** as a steward of the world;
- … a **[[46 - The Things Below#The Things Below|Thing Below]]**, or an emanation of such;
- … a **[[41 - Spirits of the Wild#**Spirits of the wild**|spirit of the wild]]**, transformed through worship;
- … the child of other gods, or of a god and a mortal;
- … a mortal, ascended/transcended/reborn;
- … a mortal, revered in death;
- … a spirit born from humanity's beliefs;
- … one of the above, but also part of a duality/triumvirate; or
- … one of the above, but died and reborn.

*Horde*, *spirit*, *coy*, *needy* **Instinct** (roll 1d4) 1 = to languish;

- 2 = to run rampant; 3 = to show off;
- 4 = to give back.

**Manifests** as flower-folk and little creatures. **Expects** first fruits, water, blood.

**Notes** Many voices talking over each other.

What is the worship of Helior like? It might be… (pick 1)

- … ancient, widespread, and well-known;
- … most common in **[[29 - Lygos and the South#Lygos and the South|Lygos and the South]]**;
- … a new thing, still unheard of by many;
- … an old thing, forgotten by most; or
- … widely persecuted.

And how is Helior properly worshipped? It might involve… (pick 1 or 2)

- … solemn hymns;
- … serene meditation;
- … joyful song;
- … ascetic denial;
- … fervent dancing;
- … formal ceremonies;
- … drugs & intoxicants; and/or
- … pain & sacrifice.

Helior has a shrine in Stonetop's pavilion of the gods. Outside of Stonetop: consider whether anyone in this community worships Helior, and where.

For any given place of worship:

- What is it? (A shrine, a hermitage, an orchard, a natural feature, etc.)
- Where is it? (In a private home, a public building, outside of town, etc.)
- How is Helior represented?
- What symbols/trappings adorn it?
- Which of his **themes** (previous page) are emphasized?
- Who tends to it?

What is this place of worship like? It might be… (pick 1)

- … given a place of high honor, above all other gods;
- … well-tended and given due respect;
- … newly established/recently restored;
- … fallen into disuse and disrepair;
- … hidden away, where only the faithful know to look;
- … some variation on the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Beyond the Huffel Peaks lies a vast expanse of water. But what lies between the mountains and the sea? That's for you and your group to decide, and the answer might vary depending on which direction you go through the mountains. But perhaps one might find...

- … mighty cliffs, pounded by relentless waves;
- … a gentle slope, a bountiful lowland, vast sandy beaches, a mild clime;
- … a chain of islands, some tiny, some quite large;
- … a wine-dark sea, the civilized lands of the south to be found at its farthest shores;
- … deserted ruins of the **[[45 - Tempest Lords#Tempest Lords|Tempest Lords]]**, the **[[18 - Forge Lords#Forge Lords|Forge Lords]]** or both;
- … the **[[51 - Ustrina#Ustrina|Ustrina]]**, in numbers far greater than anyone would suspect;
- … an isolated people, their ancestors a mix of refugees from when the **[[30 - The Makers#The Makers|Makers]]** fell;
- … colonies from the civilized lands of the **[[29 - Lygos and the South#Lygos and the South|South]]**, eking out a living;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

- Who did you once meet who claimed to have reached the far side of the Huffel Peaks? Do you believe their stories about an endless body of water?
- What legendary treasure is said to be hidden in those peaks?
- How long has it been since one of the volcanoes erupted violently? How did it affect Stonetop/Gordin's Delve/the Hillfolk?
- You don't really think that there are dragons in the Huffel Peaks, do you?

The Labyrinth is far from static. Earthquakes, volcanism, and burrowing **[[28 - The Labyrinth#**Magma worm**|magma worms]]** all wreak havoc upon it. But you could map it. You could learn its ways and find your way back to a place you had been.

But as one goes deeper, things change. The world becomes… softer. Less fixed. And beyond an uncertain point, one enters the Deeps.

The Deeps shift when you aren't looking. They reflect your fears and your desires. They seek to trap you, to twist you, to consume you. For it is here, of all the places in the world, that one is closest to the Things Below.

Why would anyone come here? Perhaps…

- … they are called by the Things Below;
- … they are lost and didn't mean to come;
- … to rescue someone;
- … to find an artifact of legend;
- … to hide something away forever; and/or
- … to do the impossible: to face and truly slay one of the Things Below.

The arid south has long been a cradle of civilization. Ruins and ancient works dot the landscape and clutter cities. Who built them, and where did those people go? That's for you and your group to decide, but perhaps these structures were built by…

- … a truly ancient people, predating even the Makers;
- … the **[[45 - Tempest Lords#Tempest Lords|Tempest Lords]]**, before their island capital was swallowed by the sea;
- … the ancestors of the **[[43 - Stone Lords#Stone Lords|Stone Lords]]**), who later migrated north;
- … an offshoot of the **[[18 - Forge Lords#Forge Lords|Forge Lords]]**, spreading out through a network of portals;
- … some other group of **[[30 - The Makers#The Makers|Makers]]**, unheard of up north;
- … ancient humans—contemporaries of the Makers, perhaps even their rivals;
- … offshoots of the **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]**, who forged human civilization from blood and fire and sand;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

The armies of the south are said to be as limitless as the stars in the sky, as countless as the leaves in the Great Wood. If they wanted, they could field legions whose soldiers outnumbered the entire population of the World's End. Thankfully, the southern nations have seen no value in invading the north. At least, not yet.

What would prompt an invasion? Perhaps…

- … a holy mandate to spread some southern faith;
- … an emperor who has united the southern nations, and now turns toward new conquests;
- … a new ruler in Lygos, obsessed with recovering the Makers' arts;
- … a dearth of arable land, timber, salt, or just living space;
- … an unquenchable thirst for slaves (or sacrifices);
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

The Makers were large and physically powerful, adept with magic, quick of mind, and they brimmed with elemental might. Individuals varied greatly in both personal power and prestige.

They were long-lived but far from immortal, and reproduced slowly (if at all). Their numbers, thus, were relatively few, and they surrounded themselves with slaves, servants, and disciples of smaller stature: humans, **[[12 - Fae#Fae|Fae]]**, **[[17 - Forest Folk#Forest Folk|Forest Folk]]**, **[[51 - Ustrina#Ustrina|Ustrina]]**, etc.

Beyond that, the nature of the Makers is for you to decide. Perhaps they were…

- … among the first sentient beings, placed here by the **[[36 - Primordial Powers#Primordial powers|primordial powers]]**;
- … children of **[[09 - Danu, the Earth Mother#Danu, the Earth Mother|Danu]]**, birthed from the elements themselves;
- … humans who elevated themselves through magic and study;
- … immigrants from across a trackless sea;
- … travelers from another world or dimension;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

The answer might well be different for each group of Makers. Maybe the Tempest Lords were among the the first sentient beings and the other Makers were once their human subjects, who stole their power as the first empire waned and fell. Or maybe the Forge Lords came from another world, but the Stone Lords were born of the hills and mountains.

Ancient writing often adorns Maker-ruins and artifacts. Most of these runes and glyphs are mundane (names, labels, memorials, directions, warnings, etc). But some Maker-marks brim with power. They bind spirits, channel energy, anchor magical effects. Many **minor arcana** (page [[57 - Appendix C - Minor Arcana#An old scroll case , fragile|508\)]] feature such writing, which PCs must decipher in order to unlock the arcana's secrets.

If a PC is literate and has some justification (such as the Well Versed move with "the Makers and their arts" as a topic), then they can Know Things to decipher Maker runes and glyphs: **on a 10+**, tell them the full meaning; **on a 7-9**, give them a vague sense of the text's meaning, or a few possible translations, and a way to learn more; **on a 6-**, maybe tell them what's required to translate the text, and/or interrupt the scene with trouble.

Other PCs can Know Things about Maker runes and glyphs, but at best they can discern a few words and recognize the magical vs. the mundane. Focus instead on who could help them translate the runes, or who might find them valuable, or places and artifacts that bear similar markings, and what the PC knows about them.

**The Makers**

If the PCs can't immediately decipher the Markings, then maybe they could…

- … show the writing to a learned elder back home;
- … Spend a few weeks referencing their collection of Books and Scrolls (if they have one);
- … confer with an **[[29 - Lygos and the South#**Dangers**|antiquarian]]**, probably in **[[22 - Gordin's Delve#Gordin's Delve|Gordin's Delve]]** or **[[32 - Marshedge#Marshedge|Marshedge]]**;
- … convince the monks up in **[[04 - Barrier Pass#Barrier Pass|Barrier Pass]]** to help;
- … seek aid from a **[[26 - Hillfolk#Upland horse|spirit-talker]]** or **[[26 - Hillfolk#Hillfolk rider|hdour]]**;
- … make a deal with a **[[41 - Spirits of the Wild#**Spirits of the wild**|spirit of the wild]]**, **[[12 - Fae#Fae|Fae]]**, **[[51 - Ustrina#Ustrina|Ustrina]]**, etc.;

- … find an intact **[[24 - Green Lords#Green Lords|Green Lord]]** tomb and beseech its mummified occupant to help; or
- … conjure the shade of a Maker or **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builder]]**, perhaps at the **[[31 - The Makers' Roads#The Makers' Roads|Crossroads]]**, and bargain for their service.

The Tempest Lords used ideographic glyphs (ideas, not sounds). The other Makers' writing was phonetic; just how distinct their alphabets were is up for you and your group to decide.

This was clearly a place of importance in the time of the Makers. Their ruins dot the Hill and extend deep below. Some of these tunnels are used as storehouses or mausoleums. Others are unexplored.

What was this place, originally? That's for you to decide, but perhaps it was…

- … a **[[43 - Stone Lords#Stone Lords|Stone Lord]]** outpost, standing watch over Ferrier's Fen;
- … the edge of a **[[24 - Green Lords#Names|Green Lord]]** city, all that's left after the Stone Lords sank much of their lands;
- … a center of trade between Green Lords and Stone Lords, abandoned when war broke out between them;
- … a Stone Lord manor, reclaimed by the **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]**;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Whatever you decide, consider writing it up as a site, with dangers and discoveries that might now be in the hands of the Old Families, the Guilds, and/or Brennan.

That's for you to decide, but perhaps it's...

- … a **[[23 - The Great Wood#**Instinct** to lure prey|hagr]]**, afflicted with some withering curse;
- … a brutal, gluttonous **[[12 - Fae#Fae|Fae]]**, and an entrance to its **[[12 - Fae#**Getting there**|domain]]**;
- … an idol or emanation of the **[[46 - The Things Below#The Things Below|Things Below]]**;
- … a passage to one of the **Fomoraij**'s [[15 - Fomoraij#Names|Names]] twisted realms;
- … a **[[10 - Death and the Undying#**Pyped**|specter]]** or a pack of **[[10 - Death and the Undying#**Pyped**|wraiths]]**, terrible and ancient and only partly bound; or
- … something else entirely.

When *you are at 0 HP and the Pale Hunter takes a trophy from you*, the Hunter claims your soul. What does he do with it? Perhaps he…

- … delivers you to the **Lady of Crows** and the Last Door [[10 - Death and the Undying#**Death's Door**|Death and the Undying]];
- … adds you to the ranks of his hounds;
- … consumes your essence in silver fire; or
- … does something different with each.

If you *escape his clutches*, you must pass through the Last Door now or linger on in the world (gain the Ghost insert).

Some ploys that might work include…

- … going **someplace he won't follow** (see below);
- … crossing running water to throw off his hounds;
- … masking one's scent with muskweed or some other pungent plant;
- … distracting him with a ghost, or something that seems to be one;
- … leading him into the path of a big, territorial creature—like a **[[23 - The Great Wood#**Instinct** to lure prey|hagr]]** or **[[23 - The Great Wood#**Cougar**|cynddaraig]]** something to slow him down;
- … getting help from a **[[12 - Fae#Fae|Fae]]** or a **[[41 - Spirits of the Wild#**Spirits of the wild**|spirit of the wild]]**; or
- … using magic to trap, ward, or hide from him and his hounds.

The Hunter's quarry might find refuge...

- … near **[[10 - Death and the Undying#Dool trees|dool trees]]**, which he seems unable to approach;
- … in certain places marked by Forest Folk **[[17 - Forest Folk#**Hooks**|glyphs]]**;
- … in one of the **[[37 - Red Groves#Red Groves|red groves]]**, perhaps, depending on the Hunter's true nature;
- … through a **[[53 - Waystones#Waystones|waystone]]**, perhaps, on the Fae paths;
- … in caves or other places too small for the Hunter to enter (though his hounds probably can); or
- … near a powerfully **[[46 - The Things Below#**1d12** origin|corrupted site]]**.

Many of these places hold dangers of their own, and the Hunter is patient and cunning. He will surround them, wait, and/or seek to flush them out as makes sense.

Why does he hunt the dead? Perhaps…

- … they are the worthiest of prey;
- … it is part of his nature to do so;
- … he owes the Lady of Crows a tithe;
- … he seeks vengeance upon them;
- … some variation of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Regardless: he will chase undead beyond the Great Wood, and sometimes catches their scent even while he does not roam the world. He then appears 1d6-1 nights later, pursuing them 'til dawn. If such a quarry survives, its only reward is that it has thrown the Hunter off its scent.

That's for you to decide. Maybe...

- … they are where **[[41 - Spirits of the Wild#**Spirits of the wild**|spirits of the wild]]** are born and where they come to die;
- … they each imprison some terrible evil;
- … they each mark the grave of a cham pion of **[[09 - Danu, the Earth Mother#Danu, the Earth Mother|Danu]]**; or
- … it's different for each grove.

Draining out of the Steplands and into the Dread River, this watercourse draws thickets, copses of cottonwood, wildlife, and wanderers to its gentle banks. The Hillfolk call it *Maengwalc* in their own tongue—"Flintwash," after the stony plateau from which its headwaters spring.

Hundreds of rills and brooks feed the Flintwash, and in its lower reaches, it's quite broad and difficult to cross. Yet ways do exist. How might a traveler get from one side to the other? Ask a PC who would know, but perhaps there is…

- … an old bridge from the time of the **[[30 - The Makers#The Makers|Makers]]**;
- … a newer bridge, built at great expense by some southern merchant or noble;
- … a shallow ford; wide, rocky and usually safe;
- … a ferry, run by enterprising souls;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

One might wish to commune with a spirit to seek knowledge or request aid. The Blessed in particular is able to sense active spirits, speak with them, and force even dormant spirits to manifest and hear them out. Some NPCs and monsters have similar powers.

Most people, though, are unaware of the spirits around them. Spirits of the wild tend to ignore individual humans. The best way for most mortals to commune with a spirit is to enter a sacred site (carefully, respectfully) and make an offering that gets the spirit's attention. One could also intentionally provoke the spirit—getting it to manifest—but that rarely ends well.

One might also seek out a spirit in its own realm. This requires shifting one's consciousness to the spirit realm, which might involve…

- … meditation;
- … imbibing drugs/alcohol;
- … exhaustion or deprivation;
- … percussion, music, dancing;
- … a guide or teacher; and/or
- … a magic item or spell.

Once a mortal's consciousness is in the spirit realm, they must find the spirit(s) in question, get their attention, and convince it to help. None of these are easy. None of these are safe. If a PC attempts such a journey, Chart a Course with them through the spirit world. Good requirements and challenges include…

- … they need a knowledgeable guide or detailed instructions;
- … they risk getting lost;
- … the way will be grueling, they risk exhaustion; and/or
- … they must watch out for **[[10 - Death and the Undying#**Pyped**|specters]]**, **[[10 - Death and the Undying#**Pyped**|wraiths]]**, or other **[[10 - Death and the Undying#**Pyped**|ghosts]]**; **[[10 - Death and the Undying#**Death and the undying**|dool spirits]]**; **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Fundamental**|fundamentals]]**; **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Primordial powers**|voidblights]]**; spirits **corrupted** by the Things Below [[46 - The Things Below#**1d12** origin|The Things Below]]; or just **elemental spirits** that are territorial, or violent, or powerful and careless.

Depending on the spirit that they seek, they might also need to surmount/brave/ cross a hazardous stretch of the spirit realm and/or risk drawing the attention of certain spirits. For example, if they sought out the spirit of **[[21 - The Golden Oak#The Golden Oak|the Golden Oak]]**, you might tell them...

- … they risk drawing the attention of the crossing's guardian; and/or
- … they need to brave the secret crossing itself, which borders the Last Door and the realm of the dead.

*Horde*, *spirit*, *restless*, *temperamental*

**Instinct** to get distracted

**Notes** Howls, moans, whispers;

By all rights, the Steplands should be lush and fertile, teeming with farms and pastures. The same storms that soak the Flats roll through these hills, and snowmelt from the Huffel Peaks feeds many streams and aquifers.

And yet: the region is rocky, almost barren in places. The slopes boast meadows of sedge and shortgrass and thickets of skinny pine, but the soil is thin and prone to erosion and mudslides. Cliffs and outcrops abound, dotted with shrubs and gnarled trees and even succulents normally found only in the south. There's life a-plenty, sure—enough to support the roaming bands of Hillfolk and their herds—but one would be hard-pressed to make a go of farming.

Why is the land like this? That's for you and your table to decide, but perhaps…

- … it's a natural result of the thirsty bedrock, the ceaseless southerly wind, the grazing of beasts;
- … the **Stone Lords**' [[43 - Stone Lords|Stone Lords]] magic still infuses the land, repelling soil and seed, fossilizing roots, devouring minerals;
- … battles between Stone Lords and the **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]** blasted the land, and only the hardiest **[[41 - Spirits of the Wild#**Spirits of the wild**|spirits of the wild]]** still dwell here;
- … the **[[46 - The Things Below#The Things Below|Things Below]]** sleep fitfully here, breathing in through lakes and sinkholes, sucking at the lifeforce of the soil;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something completely different.

A few Tempest Lords could call up a bolt of power so raw and potent that it would turn whatever it touched into glass. It was dangerous for even them to use, but no foe could stand against it.

It's possible that some device still exists that can unleash this sort of power. If so, treat it as a threat (a MacGuffin ; Instinct to tempt people into using it). It would require vast amounts of energy and involve extraordinary risks.

When you are struck by a vitrifying bolt ,  reduce your HP to 0 and roll +CON: on a 10+ , you merely suffer terrible burns and will soon be at Death's Door; on a 7-9 ,  you and your possessions are turned to jagged glass, but you might be restored; on a 6,  you die but your corpse, your soul, and your possessions are also turned into jagged glass-should the vitrification be reversed, it's as though you rolled a 6- on Death's Door.

Vitrification can be reversed, but you must decide how it's done. Perhaps it involves:

- …   vast amounts of power and great risk; …   a sympathetic link to the victim, or whatever vitrified them in the first place;
- …   the intervention of a powerful god [[20 - Gods and Religion#Gods and religion|Gods and religion]] or primordial entity [[36 - Primordial Powers#Primordial powers|Primordial powers]];
- …   spilling the life-blood of your kin upon the jagged glass;
- …   a spell of transference, where someone else becomes vitrified instead;
- …   a spiritwalker releasing the vitrified soul, and guiding it to a suitable vessel;
- …   something different for each victim, or for each source of vitrification;
- …   some combination of the above; or
- …   something else entirely.

In the aftermath of the Makers' fall, the would-be sorcerer-kings of the **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]** came to dominate the World's End. For generations, the region—and perhaps the wider world knew only horror, and suffering, and war.

And yet: the power of the Things Below waned. For centuries now, they have lain mostly quiet in the earth. What brought those dark times to an end? That's for you and your table to decide, but perhaps…

- … the **gods** themselves [[20 - Gods and Religion#Gods and religion|Gods and religion]] intervened;
- … mortal heroes worked a great binding, empowered by great sacrifice;
- … the brave and the desperate rose up across the land, toppling sorcerers and banishing horrors one-by-one;
- … the world began to heal itself and renew its bindings;
- … the Things Below—sated on destruction and woe—simply tired and withdrew;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Whatever caused the Things Below to fall back, their retreat was incomplete. Some places remain touched by their influence, some creatures stained to the heart. Objects of power linger, corrupting the unwitting, and some of these—like the sorcerers of old—dance in the dark to a nightmarish tune.

Of late, within the past generation or so, tremors have coursed through different quarters of the World's End. Do prisoners in the depths strain once more against their shackles?

The Things Below are loathe to relinquish what power they have in the world, but they can be bested with bravery, cunning, and knowledge. Some PCs (like the Blessed) will have powers or arcana that let them bind or contain the evil in a place. Absent such power, the PCs will need to Make a Plan. Consider such requirements as:

- You must learn the name of the Thing Below that taints this place You must find the seed of corruption within the site You must create/obtain \_\_, with which to bind the evil (next column) You must repair the bindings that previously held back the corruption You'll need the help of a powerful spirit/Fae It'll take days/weeks of prayer and ritual cleansing You must wait until high noon/the solstice/the equinox/the full moon The best you can do is stop it from getting worse
- It will require burning sacks of bendis root (Value 2)
- You'll risk being corrupted yourselves You'll risk making things much worse

To bind corruption, one might use…

- … a tree, especially an elder tree;
- … a large piece of stone/crystal/amber/ **[[38 - Rime Lords#Dark ice|dark ice]]**;
- … a ring of runes, deeply etched;
- … a spike/vessel of bronze, **[[18 - Forge Lords#**1d6** architectural elements|orichalcum]]**, or **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Primordial powers**|black iron]]**
- … a **[[12 - Fae#**Getting there**|Fae domain]]**;
- … a barrow/cairn/vault/urn/vessel, sealed and sanctified;
- … a perpetual holy flame;
- … the bones of a pure soul, properly carved and prepared;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

*The PCs are following the river Sruth to its source. I've decided that they'll pass a corrupted site along the river. I've no particulars in mind, so I roll a 6 for feature (tomb/barrow/memorial of the locals or their ancestors). That makes me think of the Barrow Builders* [[05 - Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]*. For themes, I roll 6 (destruction/chaos/ ruin/ignorance with "fire, ash") and 8 (corruption/disease/decay with "vermin, poison, acid, filth"). I roll a 2 for the cause (attempt to wield primordial power), and a 3 for severity (a shunned place).*

*I discard my first instinct to make it a sorcerer's tomb and decide instead that it's a cairn on a low hill, overlooking the river. Inside lie the remains of a sorcerer-king's child. The sorcerer tried to call them back from beyond the Last Door, but succeeded only in blighting the hillside with fell power. To this day, the stones are hot to the touch, steaming in rain and snow. Nothing grows there, and a swath of sickly, barren soil runs down the hill to the river, where it becomes bubbling, poisonous muck.*

Three lights can be seen every night, like ghostly flames: one among the northern bluffs, one on the south shore, the third upon (below?) the waters. **[[26 - Hillfolk#Hillfolk|Hillfolk]]** call them "the Covens" or the "the Witch Lights." They hesitate to say more.

Who or what are the Covens? That's for you to decide. But perhaps they…

- … burn in memory of the three conspiracies, or covins, that rose up against the Stone Lords, and the witches who led each one;
- … were once the "Three Stars" of Tierstered, makerglass gems burning with eternal flame;
- … are **[[05 - Barrow Builders#**Dangers**|banefires]]**, each one imprisoning an undead sorcerer;
- … are spirit-catchers, enthralling ghosts and keeping them bound;
- … are ghostly hordes standing vigil over mass graves; or
- … are some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

The fossilized bones on the hill are clearly ancient, and far bigger than anything has a right to be. But what are they the bones of? That's for you and your group to decide, but perhaps they are the bones of…

- … one of the three great beasts vanquished by **[[49 - Tor, the Rain-maker#Tor, the Rain-maker|Tor]]**;
- … one of the **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Cosmology**|First Creators]]**, slain by the **[[46 - The Things Below#The Things Below|Things Below]]** as they were imprisoned;
- … some fell beast brewed up by the **[[24 - Green Lords#Names|Green Lords]]**;
- … a mighty **[[43 - Stone Lords#**Construct**|Stone Lord construct]]**, not a creature at all;
- … a colossal **[[46 - The Things Below#**Wretch**|emanation]]** of the Things Below, a world-ending horror, vitrified by **Stormcatcher**'s [[39 - The Ruined Tower#Stormcatcher's tower|Stormcatcher’s tower]] magic;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Today, Titan Bones is little more than a landmark and a meeting place, but what was it in the past? That's for you to decide, but perhaps it was once…

- … a site sacred to the **[[30 - The Makers#The Makers|Makers]]**, a place of pilgrimage;
- … a fortress or trading post of the **[[43 - Stone Lords#Stone Lords|Stone Lords]]**;
- … one of the **Tempest Lords**' [[45 - Tempest Lords|Tempest Lords]] sky-islands, crashed or landed and (temporarily?) unable to fly;
- … part of **Stormcatcher**'s [[39 - The Ruined Tower#Stormcatcher's tower|Stormcatcher’s tower]] domain: a lookout, a laboratory, a power station, etc.;
- … a fortress from the time of the **[[05 - Barrow Builders#Barrow Builders|Barrow Builders]]**, likely **[[10 - Death and the Undying#**Death and the undying**|haunted]]** from the battles fought here;

- … a **[[46 - The Things Below#**1d12** origin|corrupted site]]**, a place of great evil, now mostly cleansed or at least contained;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Whatever you decide, consider how that interacts with your decisions about the titan's bones (see previous column). For example, if they are the bones of a great beast and the hill was once a sky-island, did the beast and sky-island bring each other low? Did the beast (or its bones) power the sky-island? Or what?

Tor is the most popular god in Stonetop. The **[[02 - The Village of Stonetop#**The village of Stonetop**|Stone]]** is sometimes called his anvil, or the quiver for his javelins. The **[[02 - The Village of Stonetop#**The village of Stonetop**|Cistern]]** is sometimes called his drinking horn. The locals use many colorful phrases that invoke his name.

What is Tor's shrine like? Perhaps it is…

- … laden with whisky and gifts, trophies and charms;
- … just a simple idol, for his true altar is the Stone;
- … home to a smoldering fire, constantly tended;
- … shrouded, held in awe, approached by only the worthy;
- … some variation on the above; or
- … something else entirely.

Clearly Tor's Fist holds some mystery, but its nature is for you to decide. Perhaps the mountain's peak holds…

- … the tomb of **[[39 - The Ruined Tower#Stormcatcher's tower|Stormcatcher]]**, or her son, or her lover;
- … a cleft, from which the **[[02 - The Village of Stonetop#**The village of Stonetop**|Stone]]** itself was carved;
- … one of the last thirteen **[[38 - Rime Lords#Rime Lords|Rime Lords]]**, still in stasis, protected by powerful **[[38 - Rime Lords#**Tulpa**|tulpas]]**;
- … a potent storm-spirit, **corrupted** by the Things Below [[46 - The Things Below#**1d12** origin|The Things Below]], but bound there by ancient Rime Lord magic;
- … the domain of a powerful, temperamental **[[12 - Fae#Fae|Fae]]**;
- … a shattered **[[36 - Primordial Powers#**Primordial powers**|portal]]**, torn open and ruined;
- … a people of great stature, who worship **[[49 - Tor, the Rain-maker#Tor, the Rain-maker|Tor]]**;
- … the last of the **[[45 - Tempest Lords#Tempest Lords|Tempest Lords]]**), grumpy and aloof;
- … some combination of the above; or
- … something else entirely.
